I recommend that all of you follow and listen to the guidelines on CDC as that is the most accurate and honest piece of information regarding this virus. And once you have it, and you recover, you will have built up immunity to which you will not get it again for a while or be able to fight it off once more. snippet.textDisplay:
I developed symptoms in late February/early March but I wasn't tested because at the time, testing kits weren't readily available. Despite travel to a hotspot, having a negative influenza test, and having the symptoms, the department of health wouldn't authorize a test because I couldn't positively identify anyone that may have been a carrier. My doctor ended up classifying it as an unknown virus so I'm essentially left with the possibility that I may have had it but no way to know.


So I ended up being really sick for about 5 days and then gradually feeling better with some unknown virus...and who knows if I passed it on to anyone else! I genuinely feel let down by the health system in the US.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm currently in the military stationed in San Diego, CA. Even though there has been 250+ confirmed cases in our county, our base is still up and running. They've shut down the gyms, and restricted the amount of people allowed to enter the chow hall to get to-go chow. On the other hand, there are still hundreds of people allowed to go in to the commissary and the exchange. Our unit still meets for work every day and we have formations of 30+ people every day. There's been 10+ confirmed community spread cases on the base itself and the military leaders don't care. I can't stay home. I want to so I can protect my family but we're forced to go into work. On behalf of us in the military that have to follow orders, we apologize if we get any of you infected and potentially hospitalized. We wish we could stay home, but we can't.
